description.plain:
‘We’ll Never Have Sex’ is a song written by 21-year-old singer, Leith Ross. The song was originally released in a TikTok video on August 29, 2021, where they played the guitar and sang the song with their eyes closed. The video immediately blew up (it’s currently at 1.1 million likes) and Ross had people in their comments demanding the song’s release.

About a month later on September 21, they posted a video with the recorded version of the song playing in the background and the caption, “guess what song we recorded today ;)”.

On March 16, 2022, Ross announced on Twitter that the song would be out on March 25th, and on March 25th, it was released.

The song is about finding someone who really truly loves you and isn’t just using you for your body. Leith also said in a TikTok comment section that it was about sexual trauma, asexuality, being trans, being queer and being gay.

annotations: You are sweetness

The use of “you are” rather then “it was” shows the love the singer has for the person as they realise the happiness they feel is directly because of them, the change in pronoun shows the progression of the relationship as the song goes on

It was simple, it was sweetness
 It was good to know

There’s an ease, a comfort, with the simplicity of being kissed just to be kissed.  Oftentimes, kissing is used as a precursor to sex and can even serve as an expectation, but the person kissing the speaker doesn’t want to do that.  They just wanted to enjoy the here and the now, the brief simple things of life, without any veiled intentions.  For the speaker, this was “good to know.”

There’s also a childlike sweetness behind the act of a simple kiss.  In the music video for the song, two young individuals (including Leith Ross) dance around in a simple manner without sexuality or romance; they’re just having fun and enjoying each other.
You look perfect, you look different

The lover appreciates how the speaker looks, but their feelings aren’t contingent on physical attraction. Now, when this lover comments indifferently on their appearance, they don’t wonder and worry if it means their lover is losing feelings for them.

Depollute me, gentle angel
 And I’ll feel the sickness less and less
Being in this healthy relationship has helped the speaker heal form past toxic relationships and traumatic experiences.

Come and kiss me, pretty baby
 Like we’ll never have sex
They can kiss, and even with knowing that they may never have sex, they both feel content just spending time together.
Let’s just sit a while
The two can sit together without expectations of anything further, just enjoying each other’s company.
I don’t wonder about your indifference
This lover is open with their feelings of love for the speaker, hence the singer does not have to question if they love them or not.

Depollute me, pretty baby
 Suck the rot right out of my bloodstream

Being with this lover removes the toxicity from their life, perhaps toxicity caused from a past relationship. An added interpretation is this lover removes Leith’s harmful and negative emotions and thoughts.

Oh, you kissed me just to kiss me
 Not to make me cry

Again the singer compares their current relationship to their previous one, saying that this is a much healthier relationship. It’s similar to the line in the first half of the song; “Oh, you kissed me just to kiss me not to take me home,” both lines telling the listener about her previous partner(s)‘ usage of affection as a form of emotional manipulation.

Oh, you kissed me just to kiss me
 Not to take me home

This new partner, as opposed to the singer’s last, gives them affection without the expectation of sex, as implied by the line, “Not to take me home.” This further drives the narrative that this relationship is healthier than the singer’s previous ones.

annotations: You are my Achille’s heel

An Achilles' heel is “a weakness in spite of overall strength”, a vulnerable area. Leith may be implying that they will always have a soft spot for this person in their heart, they will always go back to them, despite the pain of drifting away from them.

I know that I will love again
 I’ll meet someone and I’ll make amends

This line shows that Leith is currently mourning the loss of this person they were previously with. They are speaking in future tense saying that they hope things will happen in the future.

“I know that I /will/”
“I’ll meet someone”
“I’ll make amends”

These lines show that although Leith cannot do those things currently, they know that it will not always be this bad and it will eventually get better in the future.
I’ve been a liar and you’ve been a pill

This line could mean that Leith feels like a liar in the relationship or to themselves. Referring to their counterpart as a pill could mean that they caused Leith to have a distorted view of the world. Being on medications could cause one to have side effects, so this could mean that Leith’s view on life was temporarily altered while they were with this person and that’s why they felt like a liar.
You never loved the same amount

This could really mean two things here, the first one beings the loss.

Leith could be saying that they watched this person that they were previously in a relationship with not be able to move on to someone new because they were always stuck on them.

It could also allude to the idea of unequal love.
This means that during the relationship with this person, they never quite loved the same amount that Leith did. Leith seems to do most of the loving in the relationship based off of the other lines in the song, so this could be a jab at that.

I know that I would be fulfilled
 See the world and pay my bills
 Have a drink and eat my fill
 Of dinners and free will

Leith is saying that when they eventually find someone else, they will lead a fulfilling life with that person. A life full of things both fun and mundane.

‘eat my fill of dinners and free will’ could be interpreted as, I will eventually settle down with someone, having had enough ‘free will’
I’m scared to death that I’ll scream your name

This could allude to Leith having nightmares about something bad that has happened in the past. This could be the fear that in the middle of the night they would wake up screaming this person’s name and how they are terrified.

This could also allude to the idea of attachment. If Leith was with their spouse and something bad had happened and they needed help, Leith is worried that they would call out to their lover and not their spouse. They are terrified at this idea of loving someone so much that this person would be the first one that they think of in a time of need.

And honest, I can tell you now
 I’ll love you more than my future spouse

This lyric ties in with the idea of having a future spouse and the three kids previously mentioned, Leith will always prefer the lover over their spouse, that’s why they would think about running away with them instead of just saying no.

But if you come to me
 In my home with my three kids
 If you’d asked me to leave
 To be with you and split
 Well I’d at least have to think about it

This lyric could mean that in the future when Leith has a spouse and children, and their lover came back to them, they would think about running away with them rather than just saying no since the lover will always have a special place in their heart.
Commit
Could be taken in two ways— commit, (to a relationship/marriage) or commit, (suicide) The ambiguity may be left to draw a connection or similarity between the two.

description.plain:
Orlando was the second single off of Canadian singer-songwriter Leith Ross' debut album, To Learn. It was first teased on October 10th, 2021 when Ross posted a short video to TikTok wherein they performed the first and second verses of the song acoustically.

The link to pre-save the song was then made available on November 4th, 2022, accompanying a tweet announcing its release on the 11th.

The release of the song was accompanied by a music video, a lyric video, and an Instagram post from Ross wherein they said the following:

Orlando song and video are out. Joey and I had so much fun making this song into what it is, I hope you will listen to it in your cars and on your bikes and feel very very majestic and awesome. Thank you for always listening to and being so kind about my art and my feelings. Joey Landreth, you are the bestest friend and music buddy that the world has ever known and making music with you makes everything feel nice. My dear music video team, Adam Kelly, Jen Doerksen, Louis, DFC, thank you so much for bringing my little gay love story to life, you mean so much to me, To Roman Clarke, for adding a little extra something on here too, I love you so much.

When speaking about the inspiration behind the song, they said:

This one goes out to everyone who’s been in a failed situationship and you can’t figure out what happened.

annotations:
What was the day that you ceased to think of me like that?
 I don’t know what I said but I’d like the chance to take it back

The speaker finds it impossible to stop this nagging feeling of a lack of closure bothering them. “I don’t know…” is repeated multiple times throughout the song to show how hung up the speaker is on what could’ve solicited this break up, even as the song progresses.

In reality, there is usually no one singular moment where someone decides to break up with another person. The speaker feels a lack of closure from not communicating properly with their ex-lover.

You make every part of me small
 I’m short of breath and two feet tall

The speaker feels dwarfed by their ex—lover. This may be because of how highly they think of this person, making them into something bigger than they are.

Leith’s songs, particularly in Grown Up and Prayer, also contain themes of idolatry related to the feeling of being a child and feeling immature and unimportant.
I just think I was in love

description.plain:
Trigger warning: Sexual Assault

‘Guts’ is the 4th single from singer-songwriter Leith Ross' debut record. The track was first teased on June 8th, 2021 in a video on TikTok wherein Ross sat in front of the camera and sang the first chorus of the song. They captioned the video:

wrote this about a terrible man who had such a terrible effect on my life but playing it is so therapeutic. eff that guy

The first and second verse of the song (along with the chorus) was also played acoustically before the release in a video on TikTok posted on November 11th, 2021. It was captioned with five frowning faces.

On February 2nd, 2023, Ross uploaded a third video to TikTok wherein they performed the second chorus and the post-chorus. The video was captioned:

I wrote this song because I found out that the mother of someone who assaulted me was a nurse who cared for my grandfather when he was in hospice care. By all accounts, she is apparently a lovely woman and I think about it a lot. It’s also just about processing the anger and grief that comes after experiencing that kind of violence and its fallout. I can’t wait to share the rest of the song with you even though it’s also nerve-wracking.

They posted another snippet of the song on TikTok shortly after but later removed it, stating the following on Twitter:

Just posted a silly video to promote the new song because I felt like I had to but the song is about me experiencing sexual violence, and I immediately felt horrible and deleted it. I just wanna say – it’s important to have self-check-ins and boundaries when engaged with the internet, especially with our current landscape of self-promotion in music and arts. It’s an awesome tool but it shouldn’t come before your comfort or at your expense.

The link to pre-save the song was then made available on March 7th, 2023 and the release date was announced six days later.

A few hours before the actual release, Ross posted the following message on both Twitter and Instagram:

There is a song coming out tonight that is one of the more vulnerable things I’ve ever released so I just want to preface it a bit/give myself a chance to say some things before it is out in the world. This song is about the times in my life that I have been sexually assaulted/experienced any kind of sexual violence, and the ways that the people in my life have let me down after those events occurred. When I wrote it, it was to give myself permission to feel the whole range of emotions that started to consume me. It has a lot of rage, hurt, defeat, betrayal, and even forgiveness. And as much as I still hold so much anger and hurt and always will, I also just want to say that I wish for all of us, from an early age, care, tenderness, easy access to good and comprehensive FREE sex education, community, housing, free and accessible therapy and all forms of mental health care, a healthcare system that is far more just and far better at protecting/healing people than the current system we have in place, love, generosity, safe injection sites, the decriminalization of sex work, community centers with resources and without cops, and the list goes on and on. Because god knows this kind of violence is preventable and we are being failed by the systems that claim to protect us. Which, on that note, I also want to express my intense grief and love for people who have been failed by the “justice” system and by the police in this respect. Both the courts and the cops allow, perpetuate, and commit sexual violence upon our most vulnerable community members and they do not keep us safe. All this to say: practice harm reduction, keep each other safe, musicians: you know who amongst you is actively inflicting harm, and shame on you for looking the other way in the name of talent or status. And be good to each other. I love people so much, I really do, and I’m terrified and grateful and lucky enough to be able to share parts of this experience safely and publicly. To my friends and family who never wavered, who made me feel safe, I’d never be at this point without you. To Joey Landreth who cried with me and gave me his time and heart to help me figure out how to translate these feelings into sound, words cannot express how grateful I am! And to all the amazing musicians who played on this, it wouldn’t be what it is without you.

Once the song was released, Ross took to Twitter to announce that the cover art used for the single was actually going to be the same art used for their first full-length debut record, and the release date for said record was May 19th, 2023.

I told my friend about you
 He was so upset I thought he might’ve cried
 But outside on the pavement
 Well, it turned to “I like playing with the guy.”

the situation this verse seems to describe is the protagonist telling their friends about the abuse they were gettin from their abuser. The protagonist says, that at first when, they told their freinds about their abuser their friends seemed so upset with the abuser (to they point the protagonist thinks one of their friends cried beacause of the awful situation  theprotagonist was living). But at the end when their friends met the abuser their friends actullay forgave the abuser, or did´nt made a big deal out of it, because “they liked playing with the guy”. This happens to a lot to SA victims, people dont tend to belive or support them because they dont want to acknoledge that their friend is an abuser. so they often will say things like “they wouldn´t do that” discouraging the victim to report in case no one belives them.

All these feelings I can’t name yet

annotations: Someone tell me what that means

This lyric adds to its priors, saying that while the singer knows know they can only be in monogamous relationships, they don’t understand why when they always get tired of the person they’re seeing after a short amount of time. They don’t know why and they don’t know what that says about them

I fall in love
 With a different person each week
 But I can only do monogamy

With these lyrics, the singer writes about how they feel as though they are constantly falling for different people. They develop feelings for a person, then those feelings fade and they move on to another person. However, despite never being able to stay with someone for a long period of time, Ross says that they can only do monogamy.

In case you don’t know, monogamy is the practice of only dating one person at a time whereas polyamory is the practice of having multiple partners at once. Since Ross falls for different people so frequently, people may think that they should just have casual relationships but despite that maybe being more practical, they say that they cannot be in a polyamorous relationship.

Would you tell me if I was a player but the mouth of God?
 Would you tell me if you had to fake it but you loved me honestly?

These two lines are dichotomic and asks the speaker’s partner two opposite questions.

In the first line, the speaker asks their partner whether their sexual ability can make up for their emotional availability and ingenuity.

In the second line, the speaker asks whether their partner would feel a genuine connection to them even if they lacked physical satisfaction.

I want people to think
 That I am the love of their lives
 When I know they aren’t the love of mine
The speaker wants others to feel genuinely connected to them, even though they are unable to return these connections to the people in their lives.
And then I call myself cruel to be kind
The speaker rebukes their actions, but is incapable of making up for them in any genuine capacity. The only way they feel capable is in acknowledging them.

Did my lovers all think I was kind?
 And when I left, did they know I was lying?

Here, the singer wonders if their exes thought of them nicely during the relationship, if they thought that they were kind. Then, they imply that they aren’t actually kind and then when they break up with their lovers, they might catch onto that fact and think of Ross negatively looking back.
I don’t know what I leave behind

Saying that they don’t know what they leave behind, the singer implies that they don’t keep in touch with their lovers after they break up and they don’t ever really get closure. They don’t know what their exes think of them once they leave.

To say that someone has ‘been around’ in this context means that they have dated/been with a lot of different people.

description.plain:
‘Everyone I’ve Never Met’ is the lead single off of Leith Ross' debut EP, Motherwell. It was released on August 7th of 2020 and the music video came out a short while after, being posted to Youtube on August 21st of the same year.

Ross said that this song was sort of a comment on their generation’s way of forming connections:

“My generation has a habit of sacrificing and undermining the power of physical touch and human connection. I am the person who strikes up a conversation with every single nice-looking old person on the subway, and I was losing sight of that. This is a song that mourns all the things I would’ve missed out on had I not come to that realization.”

annotations:
Barstools make me sweaty
 When there’s someone I don’t know
 I probably look so stupid
 Climbing up there on my own

The second verse of this song does a great job of painting a picture of what it is like to live life with social anxiety.

You try to do something out of your comfort zone, like going to a bar by yourself, and then become hyper-aware of every slightly embarrassing thing you do.

The verse starts off by setting the scene of the narrator sitting by themself in a bar and getting nervous because they are surrounded by people they don’t know. They then begin to think about the negative ways that the people around them may interpret their actions.

Ross' height isn’t public knowledge (as far as I know) but this verse implies that they are on the shorter side. Instead of just sitting down at the bar they have to climb onto the barstool which can be a bit awkward. This causes them to worry that the other people in the bar are judging them and think they look stupid.

I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met
 I miss everyone I’ve never met

In the outro to this song, we see the titular line repeated until the track ends.

The line itself refers to the idea of loneliness due to the fact that one no longer goes out and meets people organically. The singer is almost mourning every person they never got to know because their social anxiety and lack of real-world exploration held them back.

I get my food delivered
 And my books sent to my door

Staying on theme with the rest of the song, this line speaks on some of the ways that technology has made it easier for humans to be less connected with one another.

In the past, people had to make their own food or go to a restaurant and order, which may seem like small or simple acts but they still grant you even the tiniest bit of human interaction. And while these options are still available for most people, now we can just download an app or send a text and get our food dropped off right outside the door so we don’t have to go anywhere or talk to anyone.

Getting books sent to your door is a similar story. It used to be much more common to go out in public, to a library or a store, and actually look through all of the aisles and pick out which books you wanted to get. However, now we can get any book we want with the touch of our fingers. We don’t need to go out shopping when we can just open up our laptops, search for the title of a book, and then buy it. While this may be more convenient, something is lost there too.

But from my window they are just a bumper and a light
 And I can’t see their eyes

Leith feels a disconnection from the other drivers because of the briefness of the times you see the other drivers on the road.
In this line, Leith recognises their humanity but reflects on it being hard to remember from their position as another driver.

Eyes are commonly regarded as ‘windows to the soul’ and eyes being obscured by the vehicle tells us of the impersonal nature of technology, driving and modern life.

And the man behind the bar
 Is probably lovely with his kids
 And I am just the ass who didn’t order a drink

These lines continue the story of the previous wherein you go to a bar by yourself and end up being too nervous to even order a drink.

You may realize that this fear is irrational and even try to convince yourself to calm down by imagining the bartender as a loving and caring person, but you are still unable to work up the courage.

This often leads to self-hatred/being overly critical of oneself as you feel like you made the situation awkward and came across as rude or cold for simply sitting at the bar and not interacting with anyone.

People make me nervous
 Especially in malls

This line is simply stating that the singer experiences social anxiety when around large groups of people. Malls are typically very upsetting places to be for an individual with such struggles as there are usually a lot of people all crowded together, moving quickly and chattering and bumping into each other.

Highways make me fidget
 There are way too many cars
 And I’m sure I’d like the drivers
 If we pulled aside to talk
Leith feels disconnected in today’s busy society as there is much less human connection due to fast paced life.

annotations:
Used to wake to the morning
 And feel like the world was created for me
 I used to wait for the morning so eagerly
 Sometimes I just couldn’t sleep

I believe that she is referring to her excitement before she started getting anxious again. She loved her life, and was so filled with gratitude for herself and her life that she “couldn’t sleep”. She was living at the center of the universe.

Last week I wondered if dying would feel
 Like the stories the Catholic Church told

The Bible has a lot of stories about martyrdom, and death is very rarely portrayed as the resigned, silent process it usually is.

The speaker talks about whether their death would feel as much of a glorious sacrifice or dramatic condemnation so common of the bible.

But it’s all coming back to me now
 It’s all coming back to me now
 It’s all coming back to me

In comparison to their positive experience in university/college, the speaker now talks about the decline of their mental health – referencing how previous thoughts are “coming back to them.”

This includes their missing out on lived experiences because of their mental health and unsociability.

Three years of college and I had forgotten
 How I used to find living rare

In Everyone I’ve Never Met, Leith writes about missing out on experiences because of their poor mental health and social anxiety.

Their time at university helped them to deal with these challenges and enjoy new experiences. This made them feel like they were actually ‘living.’

During college, the speaker had abandoned their childhood, being thrown into adulthood. They had forsaken the childhood joy they once knew.

body.plain: The second track of Motherwell, Grown Up deals with the idea of growing up, and particularly the feelings of loss and nostalgia that come with it. A main theme throughout is wondering how so much has changed so fast, amplifying said loss and nostalgia.

annotations: Losing your balance, and then losing a tooth

This line reminisces on important moments that everyone goes through when they’re growing up.

The first part is about learning how to walk and the second is about losing your baby teeth. These moments are placed directly after each other as a comment on how fast we grow up.

Most people learn to walk sometime between about ten and eighteen months old and lose their first tooth when they are around six or seven.

There is usually a significant amount of time that passes in between these events but looking back, you might not really account for all of that time.

I can remember the feeling of being small
 Praying to a god I don’t believe in to grow tall

The first thing to note about this line is that the narrator says they used to pray to a god that they don’t believe in.

One way to interpret this line is that the person singing never truly believed in god, even when they were little. However, despite their lack of faith, they were taught that they should believe in god, resulting in them consistently praying, even when though they didn’t believe in whatever they were praying to.

Another interpretation is that they used to believe in god when they were younger, but somewhere along the way they stopped. This would make sense as one of the major themes throughout this song is growing up and having your beliefs change.

Another thing worth mentioning when dissecting this line is that they said they were praying to grow tall. At first glance, this may seem like they are only talking about height, which could be true, but this line could also mean that they used to pray that their childhood would end soon. I think a lot of people dream of being an adult when they’re younger as they imagine it grants you all the freedom and knowledge in the world and then they grow up and realize how much simpler everything was when they were a kid.

Ross also touches on their experiences with religion in track four of Motherwell, a song entitled Prayer.

Where does it go?
 So fast and so slow?
 And so, you notice you got old
 Where does it go?
 Like how spring melts the snow?
 One day, you’re living on your own

The chorus of this song touches on the idea that we are all taught that life is short- and it is, but you never really notice how much time has passed until you look back.

When you’re in the moment, it might feel like your life is going by painfully slowly- like every day lasts a full year. But then when you’re older and you stumble upon past memories, it feels like they just happened and you’re left wondering how time could’ve passed so quickly. I also think that this is something that happens more as you get older and gain a better grasp on time and become busier, it feels like days just fly by.

I can remember believing
 That my parents were gods

When we’re little, I think a lot of us tend to romanticize our parents. They’re so much older and have experienced so much more than us. It seems as though they have the answers to everything.

However, as we grow up, we realize our parents are not heroes, they are not gods, they’re people. They’re just like us.

Oh, what a wonderful feeling
 To own and operate your life
 Oh, what a terrible burden
 All my decisions are mine

The feelings of freedom when moving out of your parent’s home are bittersweet.

On one hand, you now have the ability to make your own decisions and the freedom to choose whatever you want to do and whoever you want to be.

On the other hand, you are now responsible for every mistake you make. When you’re younger and you live with your family, you can (usually) count on them to help you when you slip up and while a lot of families still offer that support once their children move out, it’s not the same. You have to learn what’s right for you and what you want on your own and usually, you have to learn it the hard way.
